<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Bid 0 to let the opponent starts.<br />
In this case, avoid to double move until site 3,try to settle down your fellow by playing all companions you have.<br />
When you feel ok, stop thinking and run !!! <br />
Don&#39;t worry about the companions, they&#39;re here to die or to be discarded (except Gandalf )...<br />
<br />
The shadow side ( all the deck in fact ;-) ) is a bet i did with friends to show them <br />
that a good southron deck may be dangerous...So, try to use wisely the archery skills of the raiders,<br />
but don&#39;t be afraid to lose one of them after it deals his wound(s).<br />
<br />
In short, you have to apply an easiest strategy :<br />
1 Exert companions with archery skills.<br />
2 Win main skirmishes involving your powerful minions.<br />
3 Stack tokens on the AftS to deal more exertions and give you the opportunity to win more skirmishes...<br />
 <br />
This shadow part is quite polyvalent in my opinion, it punishes burdens with Legions,<br />
big fellowship with On the March, and Ringbound Decks with Southron Assassin.<br />
<br />
Against Gondor-Rohan decks, you can apply this tips but be careful to Help in Doubt and Need.<br />
That&#39;s why i prefer to exert the companions composing the starting fellowship (usually Eomer and Eowyn or Theoden)<br />
or companions which can not be healed so i can deal with the others easily.<br />
<br />
Hope you will appreciate this deck, i&#39;m waiting for your (positives) notices...<br />
 <br />
